<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<?xml-stylesheet type="text/xsl" href="index.xsl"?>
<!--
When applying just the CSS, it's like what we've got in Wikidata, just showing the data.

You could even imagine it being like the underlying Solid Pod,
and applying the XSL transformation, we're just getting a new view of the Solid Pod
(but in this case it's a website).

You can always have multiple XSL transformations for other things.
If we don't just want the raw XML to be styled with CSS,
perhaps a different transformation is showing all the user data in a Pod-esque way.
-->
<!--<?xml-stylesheet href="spiffy/spiffy.css"?>-->
<root>

	<!--
	The beautiful part of all this is that I don't need to provide a UI to input all this data.
	Instead, I can rely on 3rd party Solid compliant apps to input all the data.

	* to input watched movies, I can rely on Media Kraken to input the stuff I've watched (or use Judge).
	* A Solid compatible text editor could take blog posts that you've written and automatically publish it to the web (other
	Solid compatible services could take these blog posts and publish them to other platforms, e.g., Mastodon, either in
	full or as links to the website).

	All this stuff is synced to Solid, and then I can take that, and I've got the index.xml.
	-->
